## 7. What not to do

- Do not relocate code and call it architecture. Moving a function from file A to file B without changing its dependency structure, contract shape, or boundary design is not a fix.
- Do not preserve bad structure because it exists. If the current code violates these rules, the fix is to redesign, not to work around.
- Do not rush. One correctly structured module is worth more than ten relocated functions.
- Do not add abstraction layers that have one caller and one implementation. That is ceremony, not architecture.
- Do not create generic patterns (Repository[T], Service[T]) in a codebase with 5-15 entities per context. They will never pay for themselves.
- Do not decrease test coverage. If new abstractions are harder to test than the concrete code they replace, the abstraction is wrong.
